  "summary": "During a conversation, Lyn admits to harboring a grudge against Rosalyn and others regarding \"unjust wealth.\" David Hunter questions Lyn about her marriage to Rolly Claude, whom he dismisses as an idiot, but Lyn defensively refuses to explain her relationship. David then recounts Rosalyn’s history, characterizing her as a \"fool with luck.\" He explains that after a failed acting career and a marriage to an intellectual Nigerian official in Cape Town, Rosalyn received a large life insurance payout following his death from fever. She later married Gordon Claude in New York, but he was killed by a bomb only two weeks later, leaving her with a substantial income, jewelry, and a large house. David reveals his own motive: an Irishman who fought for England and joined the Allied Commandos, he followed Rosalyn to London after hearing of her marriage and wealth.\n\nLater, at breakfast in the English countryside, Rosalyn expresses an urgent desire to return to America, complaining about her proximity to the Claude family. David expresses pleasure in seeing the Claude family suffer from jealousy and resentment, labeling them \"little fleas\" and suggesting they might even attempt to poison her. While David insists they are staying in the countryside for Rosalyn's health and to avoid the trauma of the London bombings, Rosalyn remains suspicious. She asks David if his presence is actually due to a woman she encountered one night, a girl serving in the Women's Royal Naval Service.",
